    "text": "Menu\nMember-supported news for Southern California\nShow Search\nDONATE\nKPCC\nOn Point\nNEXT UP:\n3:00 PM\nMarketplace\nLive Stream\nSupport for KPCC comes from:\nBecome a KPCC Sponsor\nYou Make Public Radio Strong on KPCC\nSupport trustworthy news from KPCC and NPR by becoming a sustaining member today.\nMonthly (best way to give!) One-Time Donation\n$5/mo\n$10/mo\n$15/mo\n$125/mo - Leadership Circle\nSUBMIT\nLively and in-depth discussions of city news, politics, science, entertainment, the arts, and more.\n5 hours ago\nDay 3 Of House Speaker Vote & How Local Republicans Are Reacting\nToday on AirTalk, three days and six failed votes, the House is still without a Speaker– the tasks that are put on halt. Also on the show, the latest FDA regulations on CBD ;TV-Talk ; and more.\n\nDay 3 Of House Speaker Vote & How Local Republicans Are Reacting\nWinter Storm Ravages Northern California\nOverused, Cliche, Or Just Annoying: The Worst Words Of 2022\nCES Kicks Off In Las Vegas. What Do Consumers Have To Look Forward To?\nThe FDA May Place Regulations on CBD Due To Safety Concerns\nTV-Talk: ‘1923,’ ‘Kaleidoscope,’ ‘I Hate Suzie Too’ & More\nLISTEN • 1:30:51\nReviews of the week's new movies, interviews with filmmakers, and discussion.\nDecember 23, 2022\nFilmWeek: ‘Babylon,’ ‘A Man Called Otto,’ ‘Puss In Boots: The Last Wish’ And More\nLarry Mantle and KPCC film critics Tim Cogshell, Andy Klein, Amy Nicholson and Charles Solomon review this weekend’s new movie releases in theaters, streaming, and on demand platforms.\n\nFilmWeek: ‘Babylon,’ ‘A Man Called Otto,’ ‘Puss In Boots: The Last Wish’ And More\n\nLISTEN • 49:36\nA three-minute rundown of the best (and worst) of this week’s film releases, including the go-to movie for the weekend.\nDecember 23, 2022\nFilmWeek Marquee: ‘Babylon,’ ‘Living’ and ‘Women Talking’\nLarry Mantle and KPCC film critics Tim Cogshell, Andy Klein and Amy Nicholson review this weekend’s new movie releases in theaters, streaming and on demand platforms — in three minutes or less!\nLISTEN • 2:44\nVIEW PROGRAM SCHEDULE\nSouthern California Public Radio Statement In Support of AAPI Communities\nMarch 22, 2021\nOver the last year, we have been reporting on an alarming increase in violence against Asian American and Pacific Islander communities. The last week has been particularly traumatizing.\nSouthern California Public Radio Statement on Black Lives Matter\nJune 25, 2020\nAs an organization we condemn systemic racism — and racism of any kind — and remain committed to reflecting the diverse communities we serve. With that in mind, we say the statement “Black Lives Matter” reinforces our commitment.\nSign up for the KPCC Insider\nInside information about your favorite programs, community event highlights, and exclusive benefits for KPCC listeners.\nSUBSCRIBE\nFrom Our Partner\nHow To LA\nWe’re here to help curious Angelenos connect with others, discover the new, navigate the confusing, and even drive some change along the way. Host Brian De Los Santos brings you stories about L.A., for L.A., by L.A. — with your help.\nRead on LAist\nDonate Your Vehicle to KPCC\nIt’s easy, and you could get a nice tax deduction.\nGIVE TODAY\nLatest Headlines From Our Partner Site, LAist.Com\nMany Families With Unaffordable Employer Coverage Now Eligible for Covered California Subsidies\n30 minutes ago\nYour Los Angeles Storm Questions, Answered\n1 hour ago\nCalifornia Campuses Try To Lower College Costs With Free Transit\n2 hours ago\nNew Rules To Let Inmates Enroll In Medi-Cal Before They Leave Prison\n2 hours ago\nHow Our Perception Of Time Shapes Our Approach To Climate Change\n7 hours ago\nCalifornia Is In A State Of Emergency. Here’s What LA Can Expect From The Storm\n7 hours ago\nSupport for KPCC comes from:\nBecome a KPCC Sponsor\nKPCC Newscast\nLatest KPCC Newscast from January 5 at 1:32pm\nUpdated 1/5 at 1:35 PM\nPrograms and Podcasts\nMorning Edition\nAll Things Considered\nWeekend Edition Saturday\nWeekend Edition Sunday\nWait Wait...Don't Tell Me!\n1A\nAirTalk\nAmerica, Are We Ready?\nSEE ALL SHOWS\nSupport for KPCC comes from:\nBecome a KPCC Sponsor\nLatest From NPR\nPeloton agrees to pay a $19 million fine for delay in disclosing treadmill defects\n26 minutes ago\nSony says its PlayStation 5 shortage is finally over, but it's still hard to buy\n1 hour ago\nMillions of workers are subject to noncompete agreements. They could soon be banned\n1 hour ago\nA stubborn La Nina and manmade warming are behind recent wild weather, scientists say\n2 hours ago\n'Pineapple express' storm brings more floods and topples trees in California\n3 hours ago\ntwitter\nfacebook\nKPCC is part of Southern California Public Radio (SCPR), a member-supported public media network. For the latest news, visit our partner site:\nThe Brief\nPodcasts\nEvents\n©2023 Southern California Public Radio\nAbout KPCC\nProgram Schedule\nAirTalk\nFilmWeek\nFilmWeek Marquee\nHollywood, The Sequel\nKPCC In Person\nContact Us\nKPCC Story Archive\nCareers\nNewsletters\nDonate Your Vehicle\nTerms of Use\nPrivacy\nEEO Public Reports\nFCC Public Files KPCC-FM\nFCC Public Files KUOR-FM\nFCC Public Files KVLA-FM\nFCC Public Files KJAI-FM\nFCC Applications Public Notices",
